latin-1-glyphs.notes: latin-1 excluding C0, C1 control codes

iso8859-11.notes: differs from tis-620 only in a code point mapping NBSP

windows-874.notes: tis620-2 is the name used in Xorg. the Xorg encoding also adds some PUA mappings on undefined code points

ibm-943.notes: IBM variant adding graphical characters to ms-932

windows-949.notes: Korean extended Wansung / unified Hangul code. this is an extension of euc-kr, wansung

ibm-864-graph.notes: a different ordering of the IBM graphics range specially for cp864

mac-roman.notes: microsoft's cp10000 table is pre-Euro and substitutes the capital Omega with the (equivalent) Ohm sign. 1985 mac-roman was undefined in the range 0xD9-0xFF inclusive: https://vintageapple.org/inside_o/pdf/Inside_Macintosh_Volume_I_1985.pdf#page=259

mac-cyrillic.notes: A2, B6, FF changed after mac-os 9.0. see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mac_OS_Cyrillic_encoding

next.notes: per NEXTSTEP.TXT, 7-bit range is taken identical to ascii. wikipedia suggests it's us-ascii-quotes

tis-620.notes: tis620-0 is an alias used in Xorg

windows-936.notes: glibc and many others use gbk as an alias of windows-936, though it's complicated

windows-1361.notes: Unix/BDF call the Johab encoding ksc5601.1992-3 but it's Annex 3, i.e. not the main form of ks-c-5601

ibm-932.notes: P12A variant has backslash, tilde; P120 has Yen, overline

cns-11643.Notes: CNS11643 - note that this has plane 15 (2007 standard) encoded as plane 9. Planes 10-14 (2007) are not included.

dec-special.notes: this should be overlaid on ascii

ibm-1004.notes: the name notwithstanding, an OS/2 codepage
